,Recommended,224920,13894946,"Posted: 8 January, 2015",all,Dfactor,"Legacy of Kain is a well known franchise amongst many oldschool players. Some were introduced to the series with Blood Omen, others began with Soul Reaver. While the core gameplay was different both of them shared rich story and nice voice acting. Soul Reaver is the second game in the franchise and is a direct sequel of Blood Omen.The gameplay consists of exploration, battles with vampires, boss battles, platforming and puzzle solving. While I do like the franchise I also do not have bias due to nostalgia and do not like to see the game through pink glasses. Exploration is fairly nice, game offers interesting locations and architecture and there's a lot of backtracking and hidden secrets. Battles (at least at first) are interesting, but quickly start to get redundant and boring. While the game introduces a couple of new enemies the core battle mechanics stay the same, as you advance more through the game you get more power and enemies aren't a real threat, just an annoyance to stall you a bit. Boss battles are good, but short. They're not the ""win by brute force"" type of battles as you need to find a weak point / solution to defeat the boss. Platforming is fairly frustrating as the camera and controls are far from perfect. Nothing is impossible and can be mastered after trial and error, but jumping onto series of tiny ledges can be painful, especially if you fall down and are forced to redo the entire segment. Puzzle solving is fairly Tomb Raiderish, but also gets too repetitive: ""Block puzzle A is introduced, now do it a couple of more times. Block puzzle B is introduced, now do it a couple of more times again."". The best part of the game (aside from story and voice acting) is the soundtrack. It's great and memorable, a lot of people know Soul Reaver's ""Ozar Midrashim"".The PC port has flaws. It runs on newer systems, it's possible to run at 1080p and 60fps. However, it suffers from audio issues. The music has crackling noises, dialogue skips. The only solution is to play it in software, texture unfiltered mode. Another flaw is that the hardware mode goes up to 1080p, while software mode goes up to 2160p. Makes sense, right? When compared to PS version the soundtrack is pre-recorded. It has less tracks and doesn't really change according to what's happening around you.Should you get this version of the game? That's up to you. If you can oversee no texture filtering then go for it. If you prefer better overall experience, but lower framerates then go for the PS version. Dreamcast is supposed to be the best version."
76561197994995109,Recommended,224920,24567714,"Posted: 27 July, 2016",all,PorzinGOD,"Back in my day we didnt have Dark Souls. We had Soul Reaver. The games are different in many ways, but similar in the most important. Both are very vague in pointing you in the right direction. Every bit of progress you make feels like a great accomplishment because you figured it out yourself.The biggest difference from a Souls game is combat. SR's combat isnt very difficult at all, but it functions kind of similar to DS with a lock on and dodge. But thats not the games main focus. The game is really one big puzzle. Figuring out where to go, how to get there, how to progress through the levels and even the bosses themselves are puzzles. Gameplay wise, its pretty easy to compare SR to Zelda. Only its a very dark game with a mature storyline.If you like Zelda style games and dark themes along the lines of Dark Souls or Berserk, you should do yourself a favor and try this out. Its an all time classic.Hopefully one day they reboot this series. Theres many a gamer who never got to experience the tale of Kain and Raziel. There was a sequel called Dead Sun that got canceled, but after seeing leaked footage Im glad it did. It looked average at best, didnt star Kain or Raziel and it wasnt made by Cystal Dynamics. If they bring this series back, they really should retell it. The characters and storyline might be even more relavent today then they were back then. Please Square Enix, just let it happen. And let Crystal Dynamics make it and give them a break from Tomb Raider. They earned it.+mature storyline+character design+great voice acting even by todays standards+unforgetable soundtrack+world design+save anywhere+/-box puzzles-clunky controls-easy combat-enemy variety-no 360 controller support/need to use xpadder-no subtitlesPort:I havent had as much trouble as others have reported. The game starts up just fine and only crashed on me 2 times during my playthrough. I did experience sound glitches a few times that I had to fix by restarting the game. That was kind of annoying, but not a huge issue. There is texture tearing in certain areas thats not pleasing to the eye, but its not game wide and not a deal breaker imo. I hear that the GOG version is more stable, so I would suggest you just buy the Kain games there to be on the safe side.System:Win7i5 4570HD 7850"
