,Recommended,224920,20152889,"Posted: 31 December, 2015",all,Fireeye,"Well, it appears I changed my mind on this title in retroperspect. My initial points still stand - the game's camera system often is nothing short of awful, and the Steam version is a very lackluster port that is wildly inferior to the original PS/Dreamcast versions.That being said, the game has plenty of good sides - there's an entire set of spells that sort of act as a side-quest in that you will never run into them if you just follow the main mission. The platforming generally is solid (so long as the camera doesn't get in your way), and although the combat system has its issue (with enemies thrown onto the stabby bits necessary to pernanetly kill them often magically landing next to them rather than on them), its still rewarding in its own way - the fact that you usually fight no more than 2-3 enemies at a time shows that you're fighting against powerful vampires, not jut plain old mortals.All things considered, Soul Reaver is a neat specimen of classical jump'n'run adventures, but suffers from the camera and collision issues games of its time often had to deal with. If you can tolerate the latter, it is nonetheless an enjoyable experience."
