,Not Recommended,224920,33908681,Posted: 30 July,all,Mr. Matt,"Note: I have completed the disc version on PC, played the Steam version for about an hour with a custom patch I downloaded from the Steam forum because it crashes without it for me, and loaded up with the original exe to get Steam to recognize at least a few minutes of play so I could do a review.On to my thoughts!Much like Raziel's wings, I'm very torn here. The game's visuals, camera controls, a bit of clunkiness inherent of the era the game came out in, etc...numerous things are making the game a big cringey today, even though I played and enjoyed it when it was new enough, completing the game and liking it pretty well at the time. These aspects of the game could be a little divisive for players, since it's hardnotto notice how hard it is to look up or manage the camera at times, and how Raziel's jumps can be a little tough to anticipate at times, combat's a little clunky, etc.I'm not prepared to say that Soul Reaver should just go away, though. What we have here is a bunch of great premises: a vampire turned into something else that consumes souls instead of blood, out to get revenge on the sire who wounded him, stealing powers from his brothers he destroys along the way, each of whom have mutated into freaking-cool-looking monstrosities, all while serving some mysterious cool-voiced underworld entity with fantastic voice acting and a cool setting. It has a good story and premise, great voice acting, and Iloveusing vampires' weaknesses to destroy them, such as chunking them into direct sunlight, impaling them, tossing them in water, lighting them on fire, etc.Nosgoth seems like areallycool setting that technical limitations and budgetary concerns have been hampering its exposure to the world. We see a couple of humans in very brief about-to-die moments, which would have been fun to see expanded out a little into something more, to better feel the impact of the vampire scourge on Nosgoth. Older tech also meant less foliage, wall decorations, knick-knacks/details in indoor areas, and just such a bare-bones approach.I guess what I'm getting at is that people who think the original game is perfect as is have that perfect experience they enjoy, while I would love to see a remake along the lines of the GameCube Resident Evil, in that virtually everything is improved while keeping the spirit and story of the original and all of the memorable stuff that was great. I would buy and play the living hell out of a remake of this game done with that level of improvement and modification to modernize, innovate, and yet still maintain the integrity of what matters most in the game."
